"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-advertising-4d5e82a9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">五本最佳：广告书籍</a></h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-advertising-4d5e82a9"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825028?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">复古广告档案/Alamy</span></div></div></div><p>由最近出版的小说《男人无法被拯救》的作者本·普克特 (Ben Purkert) 选择。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-advertising-4d5e82a9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读文章</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p><em>将精彩的阅读推荐发送到您的收件箱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=410&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">订阅</a>每周的图书时事通讯。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 17:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Around the World With William F. Buckley Jr.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位精力充沛的作家和编辑喜欢离开办公桌。他飞行、绘画、滑雪和航海——并写下了这一切。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590104182646082628"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825252?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">小威廉·F·巴克利 (William F. Buckley Jr.) 在他的帆船上，约。 1965年。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：杜鲁门摩尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590104182646082628"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">马修·康蒂内蒂</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 11:26 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/around-the-world-with-william-f-buckley-jr-a291ad59"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>小威廉·巴克利 (William F. Buckley Jr.) 一直很忙。从1951年25岁出版《耶鲁的上帝与人》到2008年82岁去世，这位《国家评论》杂志的创始人、美国保守派知识分子运动的领袖很少停下来喘口气。除了撰写每周三次的报纸专栏和无数的杂志文章外，巴克利还发表演讲、主持电视节目“火线”、写了 57 本书、用钢琴和羽管键琴演奏、驾驶飞机、绘画、滑雪、环球旅行和驾着他的帆船横渡大洋。他一年的活动和经验比大多数人一个世纪所能容纳的还要多。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/6fefdd53-1819-413c-97b0-a3a496f1a16a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>巴克利的敌人是乏味的。他以与反对全球共产主义和侵入性政府相同的强度来抵制懒惰。 “无聊是最致命的毒药，不言而喻，它对最舒适的人造成最严重的伤害，”他写道，并引用了索尔仁尼琴最令人难忘的人物之一：“伊万·杰尼索维奇遭受了一切——除了无聊。”巴克利从他的父亲（一位德克萨斯州石油商）那里继承了财富，但他并没有屈服于游手好闲。他的文集记录了数十年来对祖国政治、文化、社会和娱乐生活的持续参与。</p><p>今年夏天，我们有机会重温巴克利的智慧和对生活的热情。编辑兼学者比尔·米汉 (Bill Meehan) 将巴克利的旅行文章和散文收集在一本题为《入门》的书中。与此同时，出版商罗曼和利特菲尔德重新发行了巴克利四本航海书籍中的前两本——《空降》和《大西洋高中》——并由他的小说家儿子克里斯托弗进行了新的介绍。这些书令人愉快地提醒我们，这位著名的辩论家也是一位才华横溢的回忆录作家和健谈家。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a94f169b-f82a-46d9-8cd8-efa471193042.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>指出知识产权不再具有像巴克利那样团结的领导者或像巴克利那样伟大的个性，这已成为陈词滥调。这种观点虽然正确，但却忽视了他的吸引力的戏剧性和渴望的维度。今天，无论是右派还是左派，都没有像上世纪中叶的前辈那样以同样的广度和热情追求非政治利益和主题的作家。巴克利不仅对这一消息发表评论。他教导下一代，生活不仅仅是党派斗争。</p><p>巴克利具有非凡的能力，可以向观众传达他的热情并带动他们一起参与。你不必是政治保守派、飞行常客或水手，就能分享他冒险进入未知领域、经受意外风暴和在公海上航行的快乐。他的谈话风格引人入胜、信息丰富且健谈。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 16 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>威廉·F·巴克利的旅行、宏伟的国家计划时代、安·帕切特的新小说等等。</p></div></div><p>没有任何一个主题能够吸引巴克利的注意力。 “我被冒险所吸引，却被马拉松所排斥，”他写道。 “我可以被说服从飞机上跳下来，降落在死亡谷的一口井里；我永远不会被说服去徒步穿越死亡谷，或者就此而言，登上马特宏峰。对我来说，埃维尔·克尼维尔比长跑运动员更有意义。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/1a5034d1-f516-4ff9-9d8f-2bcc69824ffc.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>成为比尔·巴克利（Bill Buckley）真是令人兴奋，他渴望让其他人也能享受其中的乐趣。通过他精致的感性和高雅的品味来替代生活是一种乐趣。游艇上的鸡尾酒时光、东方快车上的美食晚餐、在瑞士格施塔德滑雪、探索泰坦尼克号残骸——巴克利的描述让读者能够进入我们大多数人永远不会去的地方。 “我倾向于乘坐头等舱旅行，”他在 1996 年发表的一篇有关航空旅行的文章中写道，“这要归功于我自己客户的热情好客，以及多年来我通过大量汗水培养起来的享乐主义倾向。”</p><p> “四处走走”的范围很广。巴克利访问以色列、意大利和苏联的详细记录中穿插着对行李重量限制和商业航班上缺少椒盐卷饼的哀叹。在一页上，他参观了水疗中心，并评估了慢跑与骑自行车的优点；接下来，他踏上了协和式飞机的环球之旅。累积的效果就像与一位有趣的用餐伙伴一起度过一个晚上。酒香四溢，谈笑风生。</p><p>巴克利是一位冠军名人。他对同事和对手的提及构成了 20 世纪 70 年代和 80 年代的名人录。年轻的读者可能很难辨认这些页面上出现的名人的名字，从演员大卫·尼文到文学评论家休·肯纳，从经济学家约翰·肯尼思·加尔布雷思到专栏作家安东尼·刘易斯和哈里特·范·霍恩。</p><p>这些被遗忘的人物和事件并不妨碍享受。它们邀请人们更多地了解前一个时代喧闹的知识生活。它们提醒我们，上个世纪的美国人受益于共享参考和共同经验的厚重中庸文化。</p><p>无论巴克利出国旅行多远，他总是回到他最喜欢的消遣：航海。 Meehan 先生收藏的第一件作品是 1958 年的船上作品，最后一件作品也是 2004 年的作品。巴克利一生中拥有四艘游艇：Panic、Suzy Wong、Cyrano 和 Patito。每艘船都出现在《Getting About》中，巴克利作为乘客登上、包租巡航或用作水肺潜水和游泳平台的许多其他船只也是如此。吸引巴克利来到船上的不仅是它们带来的身体和精神挑战，还有它们提供的自由感和可能性。他在《Getting About》中转载的一篇文章中写道：“海洋是地球上最后一个可以完全自发运动的区域。”</p><p> 《Airborne》首次出版于 1976 年，描述了西哈诺号 (Cyrano) 的一次跨大西洋巡航。他和船员于1975年5月30日从迈阿密出发，中途经停百慕大和亚速尔群岛，并于6月30日抵达西班牙马贝拉。旅程并不顺利。设备坏了。暴雨爆发。船有搁浅的危险。巴克利在这些挫折中微笑着，用海洋故事和格言迷住读者（“我最快乐的迷信是，如果我在咖啡里加糖精，我就可以吃热软糖圣代作为甜点”）。</p><p>陪伴巴克利的是他的嫂子、几个亲密的朋友和刚从耶鲁大学毕业的克里斯托弗。巴克利告诉他的同伴们记录他们的想法和印象。 《空降兵》的页面因引用他们的期刊，尤其是克里斯托弗的期刊而变得生动活泼。年轻的巴克利的天赋已经很平淡了。他直接、有力、简洁的声音与他父亲巴洛克式的散文相得益彰。 “比尔阿姨（克里斯托弗对凯瑟琳阿姨的昵称）在 B 舱的药箱旁边睡得很香，”克里斯托弗在一篇典型的日记中写道。 “美国医学会、加州红十字会和蓝盾的全部知识和技术都被塞进、压缩并分隔成一个深海渔具盒。”</p><p>对于比尔·巴克利来说，航海的目的不仅是为了到达目的地，也是为了享受良好的陪伴。幽默是通过的必要条件。 《空降兵》中的水手们举办派对、陷入困境、开玩笑、玩游戏。例如，无论谁喝完一瓶酒，都必须写下一份反共声明，将其放入瓶子内，然后将其扔到海里。 “有人贡献了。 。 。 “中央情报局将保证在收到此消息后进行一（1）次免费暗杀。” ”</p><p> 《空降奇兵》大获成功，激发了续集《大西洋高调》的灵感，讲述了巴克利在第一次航行五年后进行的第二次跨大西洋航行。几次缺席使得《大西洋高中》的吸引力略低于其前身。一方面，克里斯托弗失踪了——他正忙着写他的第一本书。更重要的是，船只不同。巴克利非常喜欢他翻新的西拉诺，以至于它成为了另一个角色，第一个叙事的参与者。</p><p>相比之下，“海神号”——“任何打算登船并留在船上的人都将其发音为天神号”——有另一个船主和自己的船长。巴克利在西拉诺号上带来的定制细节、家庭纽带和家的舒适感都消失了，取而代之的是不熟悉的船员、一名专业摄影师和一位生病的远方熟人。巴克利热爱航海的品质——自发性和友谊——被削弱了。</p><p>尽管如此，《大西洋高中》仍然包含了第一本书所没有的内容。巴克利用了一章的时间回复他的信件。他对写拒绝信的最佳方式提出了自己的看法：“关键是简洁——没有办法放纵扩张的冲动并继续手头的事情，除非你准备好受到严重的歧视——即，向[假设的贡献者]琼斯发送一封很长的信，并忽略接下来的二十封信。”他还指导如何最好地拒绝各种请求。他发现，尽管他不愿意增加日程安排，但他经常答应。 “最大的敌人是：1）年轻人（其中一些你无法拒绝），2）其他编辑。”即使在 Sealestial 上，巴克利也发现自己陷入了公共辩论和职业阴谋的世界。</p><p>事实上，他可能喜欢航海，因为航海可以集中他的注意力，限制他的行动并迫使他保持静止。 2004 年，他在《大西洋月刊》上写道：“当你在港口时，可能会有四个志趣相投的人围坐在桌子旁，一边吃喝聊天，一边听音乐、抽雪茄，还有风、冰雹和外面的温度。”面对和面对。在这里，在你安全的小锚地里，是大自然子宫中生活乐趣的复合体。”</p><p>这些幸福、宁静和沉思的时刻启发了巴克利。在《大西洋高中》的结尾，当旅程结束时，巴克利想独自一人在海狮号上。他在日记中提出了一些观察结果，但发现很难表达他的满足感。 “我现在无法解读这十几个单词，”他写道。 “它们难以辨认。但我知道他们说什么。知道他们表达什么。感激。”</p><p>巴克利的写作充满了这种感激之情。他对他的信仰、他的国家、他的家人、他的朋友、他的礼物和他的好运感到​​感激。正如这些书所表明的那样，他也给了我们其他人很多值得感激的东西。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。康蒂内蒂是美国企业研究所的高级研究员，也是《右派：美国保守主义的百年战争》一书的作者，该书现已出版平装本。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/around-the-world-with-william-f-buckley-jr-a291ad59</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/around-the-world-with-william-f-buckley-jr-a291ad59<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Project-State and Its Rivals’ Review: Making a Nation Work]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在 20 世纪初争夺全球主导地位的竞争中，各国政府接受了动员公民参与巨大努力的想法。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108000987149766"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825022?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">意大利法西斯党的宣传海报。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：环球历史档案馆/环球图像集团/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108000987149766"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">保罗·肯尼迪</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 11:20 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-project-state-and-its-rivals-review-making-the-nation-work-3d73391"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> 19世纪下半叶，西方民族国家之间的生活和政治变得越来越复杂。推动这一趋势的无疑是快速发展的工业化及其诸多“连锁反应”。用大卫·兰德斯 (David Landes) 1969 年出版的书中的好话来说，大量新技术和快速经济增长是“不受束缚的普罗米修斯”，它们推动了各种变革，并以各种方式震撼了社会。反过来，各种类型的政客——右翼、左翼和中间派——都觉得他们必须做出回应。有些人直言不讳地反对任何新事物（旧的普鲁士保守派方法），有些人则彻底推翻了一切（列宁的方法）。其他人试图弄清楚如何改善民族国家的运作方式，履行其承诺并满足其公民的需求。然而，最后一个选择需要一个激进的国家，或者用某些社会科学家喜欢的另一个术语来说，“项目国家”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a2bbfa22-b941-49cf-b2ef-b4c974c2e5ec.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>查尔斯·迈尔（Charles Maier）最新的雄心勃勃的著作《项目国家及其竞争对手》概述了这种政体是如何形成的以及它们对世界意味着什么。 “项目国家没有什么硬性规定，”迈尔写道，“但它需要一定程度的自我意识野心。其领导人制定了他们认为远远超出普通行政管理的议程，无论是在社会变革还是国家权威方面。他们感受到了历史的召唤。”</p><p>随着20世纪初的大国相互竞争，它们的政府变得越来越积极：除了国内压力之外，竞争性的国际秩序也提供了内部改革的动力。例如，提高社会教育技能需要进行许多学校改革，或许还需要创建技术大学。创建一支由数百万强​​壮、健康的年轻人组成的国家军队意味着公共卫生的巨大改善。在第一次世界大战爆发之前，这种情况已经在一些国家（德意志帝国、爱德华七世时期的英国）发生，而这场巨大的冲突激起了许多其他国家对提高效率和进一步国家进步的需求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 16 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>威廉·F·巴克利的旅行、宏伟的国家计划时代、安·帕切特的新小说等等。</p></div></div><p>战争引发的新意识形态和政体反过来又强化了这一趋势。例如，墨索里尼的法西斯意大利就是典型的项目国家，修建高速公路，排干蓬蒂沼泽的水，让意大利年轻人穿上军装。可以说，这就是罗斯福新政的愿景。希特勒的第三帝国在某种程度上是一个巨大的、扭曲的项目国家，就像斯大林的共产主义政权一样：一大批科研人员从事从农业改进到原子能等各个领域的工作，而数百万其他俄罗斯人则被派往苏联。古拉格所谓的“再教育”。</p><p>迈尔承认，“项目国家”的概念可以用来“描述未来半个世纪中相互激烈对立的政权的特征”。这些领导人的共同点是，他们“相信政治机构应该而且能够果断地重塑公民社会”。政治领导（通常具有超凡魅力）很重要，设计“项目”并为其进行宣传的公共知识分子也很重要。许多项目，例如林登·约翰逊的反贫困战争，其语言都带有某种军事色彩。</p><p>大国并不是唯一的项目国家；它们也是项目国家。他们只是最大的。在 20 世纪，还有许多其他的人。其中一些国家并不在发达的资本主义社会，而是在印度或巴西等大型发展中国家，那里的右翼或左翼改革派政府时不时地与积极主动的民政管理者一起推动变革，无论人民是否喜欢。 。</p><p>如此庞大而复杂的故事——实际上是“二十世纪和二十一世纪的新历史”——催生了一本庞大而复杂的书。但这对于迈尔先生来说是意料之中的，他是哈佛大学最有成就的现代历史学家之一。距离他向我们展示他的第一部巨著《重塑资产阶级欧洲：第一次世界大战后十年法国、德国和意大利的稳定》（1975）以来，已经过去了近 50 年。其他影片则以令人生畏的规律性紧随其后，其中许多都带有精辟的标题：《寻求稳定》（1987年）、《不可掌握的过去》（1988年）、《解散》（1997年）、《帝国之间》（2006年）、《利维坦2.0》（ 2014），“一旦在边界内”（2016）。他的学术广度总是令人印象深刻，他对社会变革——现代企业结构、大众政治、国际经济、种族和地区变体的研究也是如此。他经常引用法语、德语、意大利语和英语的书籍和其他著作。他可能会说，如果他的工作很复杂，有时甚至很困难，那是因为我们人类过去 125 年的斗争也是如此。</p><p> 《项目国家及其竞争对手》共 400 页，共 10 个大章节，大致按时间顺序排列；每一章都有进一步的细分，迈尔先生试图应对世界上发生的一切，比如 20 世纪 70 年代这样一个复杂的十年。坦率地说，非专业读者可能会对本书的规模和复杂性感到畏惧。</p><p>许多年前，在观察学者们如何争论另一个伟大时代（英国内战的到来）时，才华横溢的 JH Hexter 断言历史学家可以分为两大阵营——“Lumpers”，他们以广泛的主张和努力写作以及“分裂者”，他们喜欢向我们展示过去任何时期的许多变化和例外。</p><p>如果迈尔先生以“分裂者”的身份写作，那是因为他想忠实于自己关于现代世界正在发生的事情的广泛论点。他还想诚实地表达自己对于人类是否仍然可以以任何方式进步的深深不确定性。作者承认，如果政治自由被牺牲、强人获得权力、失望的人民放弃民主和社会自由，提高生活水平的经济措施根本不够。</p><p> 20 世纪的许多历史——尤其是那些在选民投票支持克林顿、布莱尔、默克尔和奥巴马政府的短暂而愉快的时代所写的历史——都描述了政治和社会成果的稳步上升。相比之下，迈尔先生的作品却在接近尾声时步履蹒跚。他认为撒切尔和里根等人物的“新自由主义”经济和政府改革，无论多么必要，都是反对“项目国家”的举措。共产主义欧洲的垮台也让某种政治弥赛亚主义名声扫地。 “如果历史在二十世纪末停止，”他写道，“法律的新精神——回忆一下孟德斯鸠的基本社会政治共识术语——将是傲慢的资本家和被认为是社会民主党人的融合，他们着迷于他们的发现市场。”并提醒读者，本书的完整标题是“项目国家及其竞争对手”。</p><p>但迈尔先生目前心目中的对手似乎并不是反政府的新自由主义者，而是新一代的政治家，他们对于如何利用自己的权力重塑自己的国家形象，似乎有着旧日那种趾高气扬的自信。社会。威权主义，无论是在东欧还是在非洲，它本身就可以是一个“项目”，或者至少通过其许多项目抓住了公众的思想。事实上，该书最后一章的标题是“民粹主义主张和威权主义的回归”。</p><p>因此，这本书的许多早期部分都充满了活力和智慧的优雅，最终却步履蹒跚地结束了。我认为，情况并不是作者本人已经耗尽了精力，而是他感觉到一两代人之前的进步主义假设（当然是他自己的假设）遭到了广泛的抵制。</p><p>他承认，莫迪、埃尔多安、博尔索纳罗、特朗普、欧尔班和普京等领导人的煽动性吸引力有很多是可以理解的，这让迈尔先生非常担心。他很诚实地认为，孟德斯鸠、斯密和密尔所预见的西方民主轨迹可能正在支离破碎。具有讽刺意味的是，正是迈尔先生对我们民主秩序的脆弱性以及对 21 世纪第三个十年中反民主冲动的相当大力量的公开担忧，使得《项目国家及其竞争对手》成为一本会持续。</p><p>它具有弗里茨·斯特恩（Fritz Stern）的《文化绝望的政治》（1961）和阿普·桑顿（AP Thornton）的《帝国理念及其敌人》（1959）等著作的“宏大性”。但它比其他作品更重要，因为它是我们这个动荡时代的知识标记。虽然他坚持早期的希望，即项目国家（以各种方式）将推进我们人类的朝圣之路，但他也不愿意将进步的反对者视为一种短暂的现象，注定要被扔进历史的垃圾箱。他们存在于许多国家，他们的政治和社会阻力是真实存在的。如果这本书的最后几页摇摆不定，那是因为迈尔先生担心我们的民主世界出现摇摇欲坠的迹象。</p><p>读者有权问，他的说法完全错误吗？这位审稿人并不这么认为。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。肯尼迪是耶鲁大学历史学教授，也是许多研究的作者，包括《大国的兴衰》。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-project-state-and-its-rivals-review-making-the-nation-work-3d73391</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-project-state-and-its-rivals-review-making-the-nation-work-3d73391<category>图书</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Tom Lake’ Review: Ann Patchett’s Spotlight on the Past]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>安·帕切特的小说讲述了三姐妹寄居在自家农场里，聆听母亲成年后的戏剧故事。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590110423217352484"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824962?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Khanh Bui/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590110423217352484"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">海勒·麦卡尔平</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 11:17 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tom-lake-review-spotlight-on-the-past-62bd0ea"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> “有没有人在活着的时候意识到过生命？——每时每刻？”这个问题是由 25 岁的艾米丽·韦伯·吉布斯 (Emily Webb Gibbs) 在桑顿·怀尔德 (Thornton Wilder) 的《我们的小镇》的最后一幕中提出的。艾米丽·韦伯·吉布斯 (Emily Webb Gibbs) 最近因难产而去世，安·帕切特 (Ann Patchett) 的第九部小说光芒四射，在该小说中，怀尔德 1938 年广受欢迎的戏剧占据了重要地位。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/7bc6d6f7-2d63-47bd-89ae-89a4934b4db7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> 《汤姆·莱克》的叙述者、出生于新罕布什尔州的拉拉·凯尼森 (Lara Kenison) 非常自然地扮演了怀尔德笔下的新罕布什尔州小镇女孩这个角色，她在 16 岁到 25 岁之间曾三次扮演这个角色——这与艾米丽的年龄相同。 《我们的小镇》涵盖的生活。劳拉的前两次表演是在高中和大学期间；最后一次是1988年在密歇根州汤姆湖剧团。</p><p>三十年后，当劳拉的三个成年女儿回到家中位于密歇根州北部的苹果和樱桃农场以躲避新冠病毒大流行时，她想起了玩“我们的小镇”的经历是如何改变她的生活的。尽管面临当前的世界危机，劳拉还是很高兴能让她的女儿们回家——尤其是因为，在封锁期间缺乏季节性工人，一家人必须自己收获水果。 To help pass the time while hand-picking row upon row of sweet cherries, Lara agrees to tell them about her romance with an actor recently in the news whom she met at Tom Lake. Peter Duke went on to great fame, while Lara, although a rising star, decided to quit acting after some troubling events that summer. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">16 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> William F. Buckley&#39;s travels, the era of grand national plans, new fiction from Ann Patchett and more.</p></div></div><p> Three sisters in a cherry orchard? The playwright who springs to mind is not Thornton Wilder but Anton Chekhov. Indeed, “Tom Lake” carries echoes of Chekhov&#39;s “The Cherry Orchard” and “Three Sisters,” including the challenges of holding onto family land, a determination to seek meaningful lives through work, and the young women&#39;s ennui and yearning to escape the boonies—though Lara&#39;s two younger daughters pine not for Moscow but for their interrupted pursuits, veterinary school and an acting career. (Her oldest daughter, Emily, is slated to take over the farm.)</p><p> Despite its Chekhovian themes, “Tom Lake” owes more to “Our Town,” which Wilder once described succinctly in a preface as “an attempt to find a value above all price for the smallest events in our daily life.” Ms. Patchett&#39;s novel celebrates quotidian pleasures—such as the sight of 80-foot hemlocks in the woods that stand between the orchard and the shore of Lake Michigan&#39;s Grand Traverse Bay, or the sound of Lara&#39;s reunited daughters singing “Good night, good night, good night” as they knock against each other going up to bed after a long day in the orchard.</p><p> Lara spins a meandering, leisurely story about her nascent acting career and her passage into adulthood. She takes her sweet time describing the laughable auditions by local townspeople in her first amateur production, which taught her “nothing less than how to present myself in the world,” and a stint out in Hollywood, where her biggest thrill was being chauffeured around in limos. Her daughters grow restless during her stroll down memory lane, impatient for juicy details about her affair with Duke. “All three girls are in their twenties now, and for all their evolution and ostensible liberation, they have no interest in a story that is not about a handsome, famous man,” Lara says. “Still, I am their mother, and they understand that they will have to endure me in order to get to him.”</p><p> Lara resolutely resumes her tale at her own pace, “knowing full well that the parts they&#39;re waiting to hear are the parts I&#39;m never going to tell them.” The attention she lavishes on her early exploits may test readers&#39; patience, too, but the slow build is worth the wait.</p><p> In fact, the result is a master class in narrative—and parental!—control. Ms. Patchett glides easily between past and present, manipulating the rate and timing of the release of key information for maximum effect—such as one character&#39;s identity, and news of another&#39;s untimely demise. Lara admits to readers but not her daughters her decision to withhold some particulars, mainly sexual. “I want them to think I was better than I was,” she remarks, “and I want to tell them the truth in case the truth will be useful. Those two desires do not neatly coexist . 。 .” Later, Lara shares with readers a mortifying encounter with Duke that she&#39;s determined her family will never know about. “I&#39;ve given my girls the director&#39;s cut,” she says.</p><p> In “Bel Canto,” her bestselling fourth novel, Ms. Patchett created a society in microcosm formed by a group of South American terrorists and the high-profile executives, politicians and opera singer they have taken hostage. She does something similar with the enforced togetherness and compressed intensity of summer-stock theater, where Lara plays innocent Emily by night, rehearses Sam Shepard&#39;s steamy “Fool for Love” by day (in which she feels woefully out of her comfort zone), and spends every free minute swimming in the lake or between the sheets with her charismatic but mentally unstable co-star.</p><p> With just enough details to convey the rigors and pressures of cherry farming, “Tom Lake” allows the author of “Commonwealth” and “The Dutch House” to get on with the business at which she truly excels: monitoring the ups and downs of family and group dynamics with sensitivity. Ms. Patchett is a writer of enormous warmth who has written frequently about children struggling to find their place in blended families. In “Tom Lake,” as in her lovely essay “This Is the Story of a Happy Marriage,” she demonstrates that happy, cohesive families can be just as interesting as unhappy, fractured ones. Her novel encompasses not just sometimes prickly mother-daughter relationships but the difficulty even well-adjusted young adults have in wrapping their heads around the fact that their parents led lives full of dreams, passions, tedium, triumphs, mistakes, heartbreaks—and, yes, sex—before they were born.</p><p> In “Our Town,” one of Emily&#39;s deceased neighbors in the Grover&#39;s Corners graveyard comments bitterly that, far from living mindfully, for most people, to be alive is “to move about in a cloud of ignorance” and “spend and waste time as though you had a million years.”</p><p> The message Lara hopes to impart to her daughters is that, while she may have been ignorant and blinded by passion in her youth, over the years she has come to understand the lessons of Wilder&#39;s play. “It&#39;s not that I&#39;m unaware of the suffering and soon-to-be-more suffering in the world,” she says, “it&#39;s that I know the suffering exists beside wet grass and a bright blue sky recently scrubbed by rain. The beauty and the suffering are equally true.”</p><p> Sequestered with her family during an ominous time, Ms. Patchett&#39;s utterly appealing character is determined to appreciate even ephemeral and throwaway moments to the fullest, to “see it all and hold it for as long as I can.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ms. McAlpin reviews books regularly for the Journal, the Christian Science Monitor and NPR.org.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tom-lake-review-spotlight-on-the-past-62bd0ea</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tom-lake-review-spotlight-on-the-past-62bd0ea<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Science Fiction & Fantasy: ‘Scarlet’ by Genevieve Cogman]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A fantasy set during the French Revolution recasts the tale of the Scarlet Pimpernel in a world of noble vampires. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110411906045270"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824891?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Marie-Antoinette, Queen of France, With a Rose&#39; (1783) by Élisabeth Vigée Le Brun.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Photo12/Universal Images Group/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110411906045270"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Liz Braswell</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 11:15 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/science-fiction-fantasy-scarlet-by-genevieve-cogman-8098c5de"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Summer has few real holidays, so here&#39;s hoping you all had a delightful Bastille Day! I celebrated by playing the card game “Guillotine” with my family and reading “Scarlet” by Genevieve Cogman. The author of the popular Invisible Library series now tackles two of the bloodiest subjects in the literary world: the French Revolution, and, of course, vampires, in a lively retelling of the Scarlet Pimpernel stories by Baroness Orczy. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/35151395-a582-4333-8362-6a25f60ef140.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Eleanor Dalton works in the English household of Lady Sophie, Baroness of Basing, where she is tasked with all the sorts of mid-level drudgery a servant slowly climbing her way through the ranks could expect. She dreams of working as a dressmaker or embroiderer someday, but for now Eleanor is just glad she&#39;s no longer a scullery maid—a job whose duties include opening a vein so the Lady might enjoy a glass of her blood now and then. In this version of history, there are vampires among the nobility—“sanguinocrats,” as they are called. (In our world, that evocative term was used to describe Robespierre&#39;s bloodthirsty Reign of Terror.)</p><p> Eleanor&#39;s formidable sewing talents set her apart from her peers, but she also has one other feature of which she has been ignorant until now: a face that could be mistaken for Marie Antoinette&#39;s. Enter the League of the Scarlet Pimpernel, a secret aristocratic boys&#39; club dedicated to saving French nobility from the guillotine. They spot the resemblance and press Eleanor into their plans to rescue the imprisoned queen. Eleanor complies, for she believes the nobility do not necessarily deserve their fate. She is also promised her own shop as a reward for helping. <em>Facile</em> -peasy! </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">16 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> William F. Buckley&#39;s travels, the era of grand national plans, new fiction from Ann Patchett and more.</p></div></div><p> Except, of course, it&#39;s not. Eleanor is set upon by angry mobs, unhinged ancient vampires, and worst of all, Armand Chauvelin of the Committee for Public Safety. The only thing this “revolutionary” wants more than the death of all the aristocrats is a secure position for himself and his daughter—along with a mansion. And power.</p><p> Besides the constant threats of violence, Eleanor has to endure the social and emotional repercussions of being with the League of the Scarlet Pimpernel, but not <em>in</em> it. As a woman and a member of the common people, she has to mind her step around her aristocratic co-conspirators. When she dares to correct their presumptions about how the world works they can get testy: Lord Charles in particular always nastily puts her in her place (but he also might be falling in love with her, another problem).</p><p> Eleanor comes to realize that what she wants more than anything else is control over her own life, something which the nobility, vampires and even the sans-culottes deny her. It isn&#39;t until Eleanor is accidentally united with the bodiless spirit of a sorceress long dead—a state that comes with problems both like and unlike Eleanor&#39;s—that our heroine begins to see a way out.</p><p> “Scarlet” is a satisfying, historically accurate adventure that doesn&#39;t lean too heavily on its one fantastical invention. Two fangs up, and <em>vive la révolution!</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/science-fiction-fantasy-scarlet-by-genevieve-cogman-8098c5de</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/science-fiction-fantasy-scarlet-by-genevieve-cogman-8098c5de<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Have We Ruined Sex?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>五位作家询问，在人类最亲密的行为方面，社会是否已经迷失了方向。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000981788"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823443?width=860&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ina Jang，《华尔街日报》 </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000981788"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 10:56 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/have-we-ruined-sex-241c57eb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p class="has-drop-cap"><strong>凯蒂·罗伊夫</strong>说，我们不应该为了意识形态的一致性而监管我们的性生活。<strong>安德鲁·沙利文（Andrew Sullivan）</strong>记得他的性觉醒是在互联网和约会应用程序出现之前的时代。<strong>玛丽·哈林顿</strong>解释了为什么我们更多地谈论性，却很少享受性。<strong>科尔曼休斯</strong>问谁真正受益于“勾搭文化”。<strong>艾格尼丝·卡拉德</strong>探索了哲学可以教会我们什么关于欲望的价值。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3><strong>回到逃脱、玩耍和冒险</strong></h3><p><em>凯蒂·罗伊夫</em><br><br>如果一个女人幻想着被一个男人压倒，她是不是在上演父权剧本的替罪羊？她是过去所谓的“错误意识”的受害者吗？正如格洛丽亚·斯泰纳姆（Gloria Steinem）曾经说过的那样，某些女权主义亚文化长期以来一直相信，我们可以以某种方式“理清性和攻击性”。半个世纪前，琼·迪迪恩（Joan Didion）令人难忘地嘲笑了围绕“性关系的‘温柔’”的女权主义愿望，就好像参与者是受伤的小鸟一样。</p><p>如今，我们教室内外的谈话似乎都朝着同一个方向发展。杰出的女权主义哲学家阿米亚·斯里尼瓦桑（Amia Srinivasan）问道：“是否有责任尽我们所能地改变我们的欲望”，她提出了一个非常聪明而细致的案例。在她大学性哲学课程的一篇论文中，我女儿最近引用了女权主义学者桑德拉·巴特基（Sandra Bartky）的话：“对欲望的彻底改革显然已列入女权主义议程：我们应该用瑞德·巴特勒（Rhett Butler）压垮的幻想来换取一个。”我们夺取国家政权并重新教育他。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span>绝对一致性和遵守清单的愿望的想法是有缺陷的。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>女权主义者在喝了几杯玛格丽塔酒后“对瑞德·巴特勒进行再教育”的形象显然近乎模仿——更不用说“再教育”这个词还带有令人毛骨悚然的独裁色彩。但我们能够以某种方式监管我们的性行为以实现政治一致性的幻想比人们想象的更为普遍，甚至成为主流。</p><p>从这种话语中浮现出一种微弱的理想，即每个人在最亲密的环境中都友善、明智、完全受控、完全尊重和平等。但在我看来，这种绝对一致性的理想存在一些缺陷和净化，这种理想遵循我们有意识的头脑尽职尽责地收集的清单。这个形象忽视了一个不方便的现实，即对于许多人来说，性涉及矛盾、逃避、游戏、风险、实验、戏剧。性的吸引力恰恰在于人们不必在白天表现得令人尊敬。亲密领域逃避了，也许应该逃避，我们试图用政治信念或对父权制的厌恶之类的东西来规范它们。</p><p>有一种另类的女权主义传统承认并接受亲密生活的纠缠和复杂性——我们在权力和欲望方面是多么分裂和冲突。当西蒙娜·德·波伏娃被问及她对终身伴侣让-保罗·萨特的浪漫征服是否与她的女权主义政治相矛盾时，她说：“好吧，我不在乎……我很抱歉让女权主义者失望，但是太糟糕了，他们中的许多人只生活在理论中，而不是现实生活中。”许多年后，克里斯·克劳斯在她颇具影响力的小说《我爱迪克》中写道：“我是一个受虐狂吗？我告诉他，“不，”因为你没看到吗？发生在我身上的一切都只是因为我愿意。”</p><p><em>凯蒂·罗伊夫 (Katie Roiphe) 是纽约大学文化报道和批评项目的主任，也是最近出版的《权力笔记本》一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="956" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823448?width=700&amp;height=956" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ina Jang，《华尔街日报》</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>神秘感的丧失，无论好坏</strong></h3><p><em>安德鲁·沙利文</em></p><p>当我的荷尔蒙第一次发挥作用时，我完全蒙在鼓里。在接下来的10年里，我的性生活完全是我一个人。那是 20 世纪 70 年代，我无法接触到色情作品，甚至完全不知道自己会和另一个男人做什么，也没有任何关于同性恋的参考。</p><p>但我有我的想象力和一本素描本，我会在里面画出男人的形象。他们在某种程度上很卡通——大方的下巴和肩膀，巨大的胸部覆盖着浓密的黑毛。偶尔，周日报纸杂志上会刊登一些广告，广告中的男性都脱掉了衬衫，现在我可以闭上眼睛，看到一篇特别的社论时尚专题，其中有赤裸上身、穿着平角短裤的拳击手的照片。我把它们剪下来并粘在我的书上。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span>当我今天遇到年轻的男同性恋者时，他们已经知道一切了。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>当我第一次鼓起勇气去触碰另一个男人时，一切都是新的、不成熟的：胡茬、气味、体毛的感觉。只是这种亲密感本身就让我震惊。在那些日子里，还有奇怪的、精心设计的街头巡游舞蹈，吸引某人的目光，并且时不时地退回公寓。</p><p>当我今天遇到年轻的男同性恋者时，他们已经知道一切了。他们看过所有能想象到的色情电影。他们知道每一种可以想到的性爱姿势，并养成了相关的习惯；他们有复杂的恋物癖；他们见到的第一批男人出现在银幕上。我被迫创造自己的幻想；他们通过手机和笔记本电脑被动地接收信息，是预先包装好的、临床的、无情的、冷酷的。</p><p>几乎没有街道巡游；只是低着头不断检查应用程序。没有什么秘密。如果你在网上联系，你很可能会看到你即将见到的身体的每一寸，以及尺寸和精确的偏好。过去所有的沮丧和兴奋都被简化为点击屏幕的几秒钟。随时随地做爱从未如此简单，也从未如此无聊。</p><p>我不想神话化过去。在 20 世纪 60 年代和 70 年代，同性恋成长在很多方面都是残酷的。严格来说，直到 20 世纪 90 年代，在我自己的公寓里发生性行为都是违法的。因为艾滋病，在我性生活的头十年里，死亡徘徊在边缘，随时准备扑向我。由于艾滋病毒进入了我的血液，性生活中充满了拒绝和残忍，以及与其他艾滋病毒感染者的激烈程度，这是未来任何人都无法理解的。</p><p>这一切充满了黑暗，还有一种今天的年轻男同性恋者永远不会体验到的令人心旷神怡的兴奋。我希望他们永远不会。但那里有一些东西，一些可怕而重要的东西，我将永远记住。</p><p><em>安德鲁·沙利文撰写时事通讯“每周菜肴”。他是《孤立无援：写作精选，1989-2021》一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3><strong>收回镇压的力量</strong></h3><p><em>玛丽·哈灵顿</em></p><p>有性生殖是我们最自然、最根本的动力之一，所以我怀疑我们是否能够完全“毁掉”它。但对于人类来说，没有什么是自然而然的。这也是文化的。就性文化而言，我们遇到了麻烦。旨在让我们更加自由、更加感性的性革命，在实践中却产生了相反的效果。<br><br>尽管“性革命”一词与摇摆的六十年代有关，但它是由精神分析学家威廉·赖克（Wilhelm Reich）在三十年前创造的。赖克挑战了弗洛伊德关于压抑对文明至关重要的观点，他认为乌托邦可以通过解放人类的性欲来实现。虽然他在 20 世纪 30 年代是一个边缘人物，但后来在美国反主流文化中找到了一群狂热的听众，他们热切地接受了他的信念，即性抑制是法西斯主义的驱动力。<br><br>自 20 世纪 60 年代以来，进步的美国开始倾向于美国的解放呼声。但迄今为止，这还没有产生赖希所设想的感性的社会主义乌托邦。相反，将爱欲从压抑的束缚中解放出来的最大受益者是企业家阶层。性解放的时代同时也是花花公子俱乐部和蓬勃发展的色情产业的时代，这并非巧合。<br><br>半个世纪过去了，革命者现在成了当权者。性产业复合体渗透到文化的各个方面，智能手机为每个消费者提供了无限量的约会资料和免费观看的色情内容。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为我们对性的看法最重要的变化是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>但由此产生的性文化热吗？这是不言而喻的。近年来的大量报告表明，美国人的性行为不是更多，而是更少。而且这种情况似乎随着每一代人的发展而变得越来越糟。<br><br>资深性专栏作家玛丽亚·亚戈达在最近的一本书中指出，这并不是因为我们对性的讨论还不够。年轻人在性话语的熏陶下长大，善于从理智上分析和构建自己的性身份。但这是以牺牲真正享受性为代价的，性越自觉地带有商业、政治或身份主义的意义，性就越不那么直接令人愉悦。<br><br>对性开放的追求非但没有让世界变得更自由、更感性，反而削弱了快感。逃离国家规定的性产业复合体并不意味着解放，而是意味着克制。不再公开庆祝性行为；更多私人乐趣。不再开放；更加亲密。通过邮件发送手写的色情短信，或者什么也不发送。在 21 世纪，要真正对性持积极态度，就意味着收回压抑的力量。<br><br><em>玛丽·哈林顿 (Mary Harrington) 是 UnHerd 的特约编辑，也是《女权主义反对进步》一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="992" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823453?width=700&amp;height=992" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ina Jang，《华尔街日报》</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>联播文化及其不满</strong></h3><p><em>作者</em>：科尔曼·休斯<br></p><p>2016 年至 2020 年，当我在哥伦比亚大学读本科时，我经常讨论所谓的“勾搭文化”。粗略地说，这种想法是，在没有任何关系或承诺的情况下发生性行为是正常的、好的，而且确实是进步的。</p><p>年轻人不需要太多说服力。勾搭文化与我们的“工厂环境”非常吻合，以至于一群男性朋友几乎不会想到讨论这个问题。一群大学男生讨论勾搭文化，就像一群老派牛仔自发地讨论枪支文化的优点一样。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span>通常只需要一次可怕的、没有承诺的勾搭就能让女人知道这种规范出了问题。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>事实上，年轻女性对勾搭文化有自己的看法——在某些情况下持支持态度，在另一些情况下则持消极态度。当年轻女性反对时，通常有一个简单的理由：经验。通常只需要与一个年轻人进行一次可怕的、没有承诺的勾搭，及其心理后果，就能让她知道这种规范出了问题。</p><p>更让我惊讶的是那些支持勾搭文化的年轻女性。对他们来说，勾搭文化有一个不同的名字：“性积极性”。她们将性积极性视为女权主义对父权正统观念的一种反抗，这种正统观念因女性进行无承诺的性行为而羞辱女性，而男性也有同样行为的通行证。她们往往不喜欢男人，尤其是异性恋白人。</p><p>具有讽刺意味的是，勾搭文化的最大受益者正是他们声称不喜欢的男人。那些人自然不反对。他们非常喜欢参与其中。但他们也没有太过口头支持，以免哪个性别真正受益变得显而易见。总的来说，当女人们互相讨论这个问题时，年轻男人很乐意站在一边。</p><p>我怀疑，2010年代这么多年轻女性对大学校园性侵犯产生的道德恐慌的部分原因是——当时政客和媒体人物经常重复错误的说法，即五分之一的大学女性有性侵犯行为。受到攻击——是因为他们中的许多人对勾搭文化产生的针对年轻人的愤怒感到愤怒。</p><p>换句话说，真正的问题不是校园性侵犯的战区水平。真正的问题是一种文化，它不仅批准而且鼓励年轻人发生性行为，而不期望有任何礼貌、后续行动或承诺——尤其是男性方面。虽然她们不能因为年轻男性参与勾搭文化而生气，这被认为是一种女权主义和进步的创新，但女性可以在性侵犯问题上将愤怒发泄到年轻男性身上。</p><p>如果年轻男女想要对性和人际关系形成健康的态度，就必须诚实地讨论勾搭文化。在否认过去的父权制规范时，我们不应该在另一个方向上走得太远，以至于最终伤害了女权主义革命本应帮助的人们。</p><p><br><em>科尔曼·休斯 (Coleman Hughes) 是美国有线电视新闻网 (CNN) 的政治分析师、《自由报》的特约撰稿人以及“与科尔曼对话”播客的主持人。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3><strong>同意的平坦性</strong></h3><p><em>艾格尼丝·卡拉德</em><br><br>我们对性了解多少？看到就知道，做了就知道，知道它的意义。但当需要说明其重要性时，我们就不太确定了。我们所知道和不知道的这种模式暗示了“性是什么？”这个问题的答案。性是一种仪式。<br><br>仪式是象征性地实现一个想法的一系列行为。握手或鞠躬表达了相互认可的意思；婚礼标志着承诺的实现。对于我们难以直接表达的想法，我们往往最需要这些符号。例如，我们对死亡的想法有困难，有时会对所爱的人说：“我不敢相信她死了。”葬礼传达了这样的想法：“她不仅没有在这个或那个场合失踪；她还没有失踪。”她已经永远消失了。”睡前仪式，比如讲故事和晚安之吻，传达了这样的想法：“我仍然关心你，尽管我让你独自一人在黑暗中无所事事”——而且它比简单地说这些要好字。<br><br>性所产生的观念是最棘手的观念之一：彻底的互惠欲望。亚里士多德要求我们想象两个恋人之间的选择：第一个非常想与你发生性关系，但不能，而第二个可以并且愿意，但并不真正喜欢。亚里士多德说，如果你是一个真正好色的人，你会选择第一个。欲望之所以具有情欲，是因为它只需得到回报就能得到满足。<br><br>我可以以各种方式想要你——竞选总统、作为桥梁伙伴等等——但是当我以这种方式想要你时，我所想要的就是你以完全相同的方式想要我，那么我的欲望是性的。非性欲可能会寻求回报，但不仅仅是回报。如果我想让你和我一起去散步，你并不能通过想要和我一起去散步来满足这个愿望——因为真正的散步呢？仅仅通过反映在另一个欲望中就能满足的欲望是一种奇怪的欲望，奇怪的是我们不是直接表达这种欲望的想法，而是通过仪式的方式来实现它。性就是那种仪式。<br><br>同意的想法，或者持续的同意，或者持续的热情同意——这些都是互惠欲望的三维概念的二维投影。这就是为什么当试图捕捉性、仪式的含义时，同意感觉平淡或薄弱。我们不应感到惊讶的是，同意仅限于可以直接、非象征性表达的范围（你必须能够具体说明你同意什么），无法传达相关的想法。为了传达这个想法，我们发生了性行为。<br><br><em>艾格尼丝·卡拉德是芝加哥大学哲学教授。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/have-we-ruined-sex-241c57eb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/have-we-ruined-sex-241c57eb<category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>色情</category><category>社会问题</category><category>性别平等</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>色情</category><category>社会问题</category><category>性别平等</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Slip’ Review: A Group Biography of Dockside Artists]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In a waterfront locale in the shadow of 1950s Wall Street, Ellsworth Kelly, Robert Indiana and others found a place to make art. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108492145796672"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825015?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ellsworth Kelly at his Manhattan studio on Coenties Slip in 1961.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Fritz Goro </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108492145796672"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Hamilton Cain</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 10:42 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-slip-review-dockside-visionaries-574a78d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The Slips of lower Manhattan—sites of former ship berths on the East River, now landfill paved into streets and plazas—evoke, in our historical memory, the tall ships and chandleries of the 19th century, when trade and New York Harbor fueled the city&#39;s explosive growth. The oblong spaces and slants of light in the Slips are visually enigmatic among a forest of skyscrapers, and, at certain points open onto heaving currents and panoramic views of Brooklyn. The South Street Seaport is an ode to that past. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/46c38dea-9866-4e1e-b7ae-f47aa99e4c66.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In her marvelous, crisply written “The Slip,” Prudence Peiffer showcases a cadre of artists who resided along Coenties Slip—now a part of the Financial District near Pearl Street—in the late 1950s and &#39;60s, decades after the schooners and frigates moved to the Hudson River. By necessity these artists lived cheaply, squatting in lofts amid abandoned warehouses and toiling over canvases and sculptures. They imagined fresh possibilities in the wake of the Abstract Expressionists&#39; breakthroughs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">16 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> William F. Buckley&#39;s travels, the era of grand national plans, new fiction from Ann Patchett and more.</p></div></div><p> Ms. Peiffer, an editor at New York&#39;s Museum of Modern Art, launches her narrative with a 1958 photograph snapped by Hans Namuth, a group portrait on the tar-papered roof of 3-5 Coenties. Their postures speak to an ease among the subjects, born of the romance of being young and ambitious in New York. “The Slip” revolves around the close friendship between the gay Ellsworth Kelly and the straight Jack Youngerman, ex-GIs who&#39;d met in Paris after World War II, but Ms. Peiffer places their bond in a wider circle: Youngerman&#39;s French-Lebanese wife, actress Delphine Seyrig, destined for celluloid immortality in Alain Resnais&#39;s “Last Year at Marienbad”; the gifted Robert Indiana (born Robert Clark), briefly Kelly&#39;s lover; Lenore Tawney, who experimented with textiles; Agnes Martin, a nomadic minimalist who hid her schizophrenia; and Minnesota-raised James Rosenquist, whose graphics heralded Pop art. There are titillating cameos, too, such as Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg, whose apartment was around the corner. (They kept an aloof if polite distance.)</p><p> For its residents, Coenties was “down downtown,” outside of Manhattan; to venture across Front Street was to go “into the city.” Much of their work reacted against Abstract Expressionism, dominant in postwar American art and itself a rejection of the easel tradition. Jackson Pollock&#39;s fatal car crash on Long Island in 1956 affirmed “Ab Ex” as the reigning aesthetic by serving up a tragic myth of a genius destroyed by his own demons. The Coenties community preferred a quieter life to the “raucous, bellicose” scene at the Cedar Tavern in Greenwich Village, a favorite haunt of the Ab Ex crowd. By contrast, Youngerman said, he and his friends were “a bunch of Protestants from the hinterlands.” They staked out a couple of austere blocks ornamented only by a tangle of ginkgo trees and a lighthouse perched atop the Seaman&#39;s Church Institute, commemorating the sinking of the Titanic.</p><p> Here they explored a gamut of ideas and methods, but they were “a group brought together not by the tenets of composition or technique or even philosophy—as with Abstract Expressionism—or by a particular way of reacting or synthesizing the cultural moment, as with Pop art,” Ms. Peiffer observes. Reflecting on Namuth&#39;s rooftop photo, she asks, “What if we thought about groups in art history based instead on shared places? What if, rather than technique or style, it&#39;s a spirit of place that defines a crucial moment?”</p><p> Ms. Peiffer shifts between profiles of each figure and the neighborhood&#39;s rich past, tracking back to the colonial period: “The Slip was a modest, almost forgotten place, an alley dead-ending in shipworm- and gribbles-infested piers.” In its shapeshifting she spots “the entire history of the island in its cobblestones.” The site was a business hub from its early days, “built by enslaved people, with revolutionary meetings just down Pearl Street,” and name-checked in Melville&#39;s “Moby-Dick.” Amid cycles of trade, the Slip weathered “the boom and bust and boom and bust of maritime and light industries.”</p><p> While her transitions to and from the past are occasionally jarring, Ms. Peiffer highlights the ironic contrast between the Coenties&#39; impoverished crew and Wall Street, yards away, as well as the more subtle connections between the two. Postwar painters often trained as commercial illustrators and billboard designers, from Rosenquist to de Kooning to Warhol. Unlike European painters who drew on a centuries-long heritage of luminous chiaroscuros and vanishing points, Americans exploited the materials themselves, stripped of any obligation to representation.</p><p> Agnes Martin, the middle-aged purist, swapped arid New Mexico for harbor fog. Ms. Peiffer finds in Martin&#39;s restless movements a key to the oppositions central to her oeuvre: “Going back and forth between the city and the desert underscored a broader theme throughout her life, between separateness and community, that mimicked the great, stark contradictions of America itself . 。 。 urban drive and pastoral stillness, capitalist appetite and Calvinist restraint.” Meanwhile, Lenore Tawney&#39;s innovations in weaving—she invented new methods, tools and forms—elevated fabrics as mediums for storytelling.</p><p> Ms. Peiffer&#39;s chapters on Ellsworth Kelly and Robert Indiana are her best. A protégé of Alexander Calder, Kelly was obsessed with color—for him, “there were a thousand yellows in the world”—and his bold canvases are paeans to primary hues. His plant drawings are now staples of museums. As a teenager Indiana had studied Latin and was keen on the Greek statues called “herms,” classical pillars with male heads and carved genitals. He updated these sculptures with scraps scavenged in the neighborhood, adding words— <em>CHIEF, AHAB, TUG</em> —that alluded to his waterfront setting.</p><p> By the mid-1960s the Coenties artists had dispersed to other locales. While Ms. Peiffer&#39;s book doesn&#39;t fulfill its subtitle&#39;s claim that the Slip “changed American art forever,” it&#39;s nonetheless a vivid account of a significant moment in its history. There are still pockets of Georgian buildings along lower Manhattan&#39;s fringe, but they&#39;re overshadowed by glass towers, markers of the encroaching finance sector. “To live at the Slip was to live within a palimpsest of history,” Ms. Peiffer writes, “where the present was never quite fixed.” And where the chance to take a new departure perpetually beckoned.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Cain is the author of “This Boy&#39;s Faith: Notes from a Southern Baptist Upbringing.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-slip-review-dockside-visionaries-574a78d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-slip-review-dockside-visionaries-574a78d7<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The 272’ Review: Slaves of Georgetown]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> As cotton rose to new heights of profitability in the 1830s, the Washington, DC, college sold its remaining slaves into the Deep South. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590108160471514500"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825074?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A woman in the Franklin &amp; Armfield slave prison in Alexandria, Va., in the 1860s.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Buyenlarge/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590108160471514500"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Fergus M. Bordewich</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 10:39 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-272-review-slaves-of-georgetown-4d7cd74c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In November 1838, a sad if familiar scene played out on the docks of Alexandria, Va., as slave traders herded scores of enslaved men, women and children onto a ship bound for cotton plantations in faraway Louisiana. They were the first contingent of 272 black Americans that the Jesuits of Georgetown College were selling to prop up the school&#39;s precarious finances. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/bce49949-51fb-477d-b16b-ccba2c689879.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Rachel Swarns, a journalism professor at NYU, first learned of this long-forgotten story in 2016 while working at the New York Times. In “The 272,” she has amplified her early reporting into a vivid and compelling narrative that lays bare the complexity of these tragic events and traces, where possible, the fate of the slaves themselves.</p><p> Slavery, Ms. Swarns argues, was essential to the development of the Roman Catholic Church in America. “For more than a century,” she writes, the church “relied on the buying, selling, and enslavement of Black people to lay its foundations, support its clergy, and drive its expansion.” The proceeds from slave labor, she says, were used to build the nation&#39;s first Catholic college and cathedral, among other institutions.</p><p> Catholics from England arrived in North America in 1634 under the auspices of Cecil Calvert, Lord Baltimore, who planted his colony on the Potomac River in Maryland. He eventually allocated some 20,000 acres of his royal land grant to the Jesuits, property that evolved into a network of slave-worked plantations. Among the colony&#39;s earliest laborers, Ms. Swarns tells us, was Ann Joice, a free black Englishwoman who arrived as an indentured servant around 1676 and was forced into slavery, locking her descendants into bondage until they were freed during the Civil War. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">16 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> William F. Buckley&#39;s travels, the era of grand national plans, new fiction from Ann Patchett and more.</p></div></div><p> For generations, Maryland remained the epicenter of America&#39;s largely rural Catholic population. Their spiritual needs were served mainly by priests dispatched from Europe until the opening, in 1791, of Georgetown College, the country&#39;s first Catholic institution of higher learning. Its creation was driven by Father John Carroll, the scion of a powerful local landowning family. (Georgetown, a thriving Maryland river port, had just been incorporated into the District of Columbia.) From the start, the college attracted students from non-Catholic families, including grandnephews of George Washington, but it floundered financially. In the 1830s, new leadership under the dynamic Father Thomas Mulledy, a native Virginian and a Jesuit who had studied in Rome, set out to stabilize the college by monetizing the one asset the Jesuits had in abundance: slaves.</p><p> Some Jesuits expressed anxiety that their slaves might be sold to “heretics,” but they were largely silent on the morality of selling their fellow human beings, most of whom had lived their entire lives on the church&#39;s lands. Even as condemnation of slavery grew in Europe and in the northern United States, Mulledy scoffed at the “American mania for emancipation.”</p><p> Mulledy struck a deal with Henry Johnson, a wealthy member of Congress who wanted hands to work his vast plantations in Louisiana and agreed to buy the Jesuits&#39; slaves en masse. Johnson, a non-Catholic, was regarded as relatively benevolent by the standards of the time: He agreed not to separate families and to ensure that the enslaved had access to Catholic clergy, promises he only sometimes honored.</p><p> The sale of the Jesuits&#39; slaves contributed to the economic realignment that was taking place in the US at the time, as the old tobacco-growing economy of the Mid-Atlantic faded in importance and the production of cotton surged to new heights of profitability. In all, some one million enslaved people were forcibly removed from their homes in the upper South to toil in cotton fields from Alabama to Texas.</p><p> Meanwhile, the nation&#39;s Catholic population ballooned as immigrants poured into Northern cities from Ireland and Germany, creating an unprecedented demand for priests, churches and schools and shifting the religion&#39;s center of demographic gravity away from rural Maryland. The Jesuits of Georgetown channeled money, teachers and supplies to Catholic communities elsewhere, Ms. Swarns writes, in the process “transforming themselves from an order known as one of the largest slaveholders in Maryland to one that would become synonymous with Catholic education.” The mass sale of 1838, she says, was the “critical turning point.”</p><p> Profits from the sale streamed into the Jesuits&#39; accounts, eventually totaling more than $130,000, about $4.5 million in today&#39;s dollars. The money enabled the Jesuits to invest in Treasury notes and bonds, generating enough income to support new schools, including St. Louis University in Missouri, Holy Cross College in Massachusetts and Loyola College in Baltimore. “Without the enslaved,” Ms. Swarns claims, “the Catholic Church in the United States, as we know it today, would not exist.”</p><p> In 2021, after years of sometimes tense negotiations with descendants of the Jesuits&#39; slaves, Georgetown University agreed to establish a fund of $100 million on their behalf: Half the sum is to be distributed to organizations engaged in racial reconciliation; a quarter assigned to scholarships for descendant-students; and the remainder devoted to the emergency needs of elderly and infirm descendants.</p><p> “The 272” is neither an argument for wholesale reparations nor a polemic directed at the Catholic Church. While Ms. Swarns&#39;s heart understandably lies with the enslaved and their tragic fate, she has delivered a fair-minded account that illuminates the pragmatic motives of the Jesuits and recovers from near-oblivion the lives of the enslaved people at the center of the story.</p><p> Alongside Ms. Swarns&#39;s sharply etched portraits of Father Mulledy and other Jesuits, we meet men and women such as the patriarchal black plantation foreman Harry Mahoney, who hid the savings of the Maryland priests from marauding British troops during the War of 1812, and his African-born wife, Anna. We meet their children too: Bibiana, who was sold to slaveowners in Louisiana; Robert, who in middle age would be assessed as having “no value”; and Anna, who remained in Maryland and lived into the 20th century.</p><p> Capturing more than a wisp of individual slaves&#39; lives is a formidable challenge, given that they rarely appear as more than single names in the accounts of their enslavers. Ms. Swarns has brilliantly mined archives and oral histories to tease out buried connections and biographical details. In particular, she manages to weave a striking, if necessarily incomplete, tapestry of Ann Joice&#39;s descendants, who, we are happy to learn, thrived against the odds in both Maryland and Louisiana and rediscovered one another, 350 years after their ancestor&#39;s arrival on these shores, in the common effort to persuade Georgetown University to come to grips with its full history.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Bordewich is the author of “Klan War: Ulysses S. Grant and the Battle to Save Reconstruction,” to be published in October.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-272-review-slaves-of-georgetown-4d7cd74c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-272-review-slaves-of-georgetown-4d7cd74c<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Education</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>education</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Mysteries: Three Novels of Domestic Suspense]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Laura Lippman&#39;s &#39;Prom Mom,&#39; Megan Abbott&#39;s &#39;Beware the Woman&#39; and Susan Isaacs&#39;s &#39;Bad, Bad Seymour Brown.&#39; <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590111960757872040"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="495" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824507?width=860&amp;height=495" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590111960757872040"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-nolan" itemprop="url" rel="author">Tom Nolan</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 10:38 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries-three-novels-of-domestic-suspense-3d80fae3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Laura Lippman&#39;s latest novel, “Prom Mom,” centers on Amber Glass, a Baltimore woman whose life has been scarred by events that occurred two decades ago. On the night of her school prom, Amber passed out in a hotel room and woke up alone with the lifeless body of the baby she&#39;d just prematurely delivered. She was blamed for the infant&#39;s death, served prison time and self-exiled to New Orleans. Now she&#39;s returned to her suburban hometown to sell the old family house and open an art gallery. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a7ddabb2-428b-4ec7-868c-4089704df6d8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> What&#39;s become of Joe Simpson, the “Cad Dad” who abandoned her that night to pursue another girl? Joe got married and became an ambitious real-estate broker. It doesn&#39;t take him long to notice Amber&#39;s new gallery, and to wonder: “If he could be a friend to her now—wouldn&#39;t that be a kind of redemption?”</p><p> The timeline of “Prom Mom” toggles between the present and past as seen through different points of view. Readers&#39; sympathies shift from one character to another, as Ms. Lippman parcels out crucial information to induce gasps of surprise.</p><p> “If you wanted to have a future,” Amber reflects, “you had to let go of the past.” But what if your flaws and urges are so deeply ingrained that you&#39;re condemned to repeat them? Ms. Lippman, long recognized as a master of plot and exposition, has been serving up psychologically rich slices of karma for years. Even her most demanding fans will be tempted to judge “Prom Mom” one of her best books yet. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/8ddf541e-5168-4e69-9061-49777d718253.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Megan Abbott&#39;s “Beware the Woman” takes romantic suspense to the far edge of melodrama. The book relates the travails of Jacy, a New York schoolteacher who marries an artist and then, on becoming pregnant, heads with him to Michigan&#39;s Upper Peninsula to visit his widowed father. She doesn&#39;t know all that much about her spouse, Jed, but she&#39;s happy to the point of superstition: “In some ways it felt like being this much in love—you had to hide it . 。 。 You were tempting fate, or something.”</p><p> Jed seems reticent to return to the place where his mother died giving birth to him. He hasn&#39;t been home in over 10 years. “We could turn around and go back,” he suggests on the drive, “explain it wasn&#39;t a good time. Not with the baby coming.” But Jed then denies he&#39;s said any such thing; he insists Jacy must have been dreaming. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">16 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> William F. Buckley&#39;s travels, the era of grand national plans, new fiction from Ann Patchett and more.</p></div></div><p> Ms. Abbott&#39;s storytelling talent is on fine display here. We&#39;re gripped from the first page and soon in the spell of an enchantment. Like Jacy, we&#39;re charmed by Jed&#39;s retired father, Doctor Ash, a patrician gentleman eager to put his daughter-in-law at ease. But there&#39;s tension between the doctor and his son, and a disturbing insularity to the remote community where he lives.</p><p> “People here, we don&#39;t interfere,” the doctor&#39;s taciturn caretaker explains. “We keep to ourselves. We mind our own business. 。 。 。 You could die, you see, and no one might ever know.” The creepiness intensifies during nine claustrophobic days and nights. Shocking family revelations bring an ominous sense of dread. Whether or not one is satisfied by the book&#39;s bizarre denouement, Ms. Abbott has undeniably given us a story we&#39;ll never forget. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/d1c06a88-b667-43fe-baa8-5059a575c482.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “Bad, Bad Seymour Brown” by Susan Isaacs is the second entry of a series starring former FBI agent Corie Geller and her father, retired NYPD detective Dan Schottland. The titular Seymour Brown was a New York accountant who made his fame and fortune as a money launderer. He died, along with his wife, in an intentionally set house fire from which their five-year-old daughter, April, escaped.</p><p> Decades later, April, now a professor of film studies at Rutgers, asks Corie&#39;s dad for help. She&#39;s just survived what she&#39;s sure was an attempt to kill her. Might this attack have something to do with her parents&#39; unsolved murders? Ex-detective Dan, who&#39;s exchanged Christmas cards with April all these years, leaps at the chance to reexamine “the coldest of his cold cases.”</p><p> Both of Corie&#39;s parents, in the wake of Covid, are living with her and her husband in Long Island. Having recently survived a kidnapping (see 2019&#39;s “Takes One to Know One”), Corie is happy to co-direct the effort to deliver April from her past and present traumas.</p><p> “Getting people to talk is what I do best,” Corie claims. As a narrator, she herself is a formidable raconteur, as generous with details as Proust, as full of anecdote as a suburban Scheherazade. She and her father make a good team, pooling resources and pulling in a host of ex-colleagues and guest experts to assist them. They need all the help they can get to combat a most determined villain and save their brave and endearing client.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries-three-novels-of-domestic-suspense-3d80fae3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries-three-novels-of-domestic-suspense-3d80fae3<author><![CDATA[Tom Nolan]]></author><category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Hive’ Review: Faces in the Crowd]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nobel laureate Camilo José Cela&#39;s novel unveiled life in Madrid during the Franco era, via a rich blend of voices and personalities. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108540615376652"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824858?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Universal History Archive/Universal Images/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108540615376652"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Boyd Tonkin</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 10:31 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hive-review-fiction-madrid-faces-in-the-crowd-399854da"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Late at night, in the chilly winter of Madrid in 1943, lonely strollers drift into the movie theaters. They watch “pictures filled with attractive, poetic names that pose vast human enigmas which are not always deciphered, or answered at all.” The huge, swarming cast of “The Hive,” which the Spanish writer Camilo José Cela published in 1951, trip over those “vast human enigmas” as they try to make sense of their own discordant and disconnected lives. But life is tough, time short, money scarce. Even if love, pity or wonder briefly stir them, every citizen has a job to finish, a bill to pay, a date to meet. Passersby feel sorry for the dog crushed by a taxi in the Calle de Torrijos but “everyone goes his own way.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/04e109c5-2780-480d-bf20-300f91662547.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Throughout the 20th century, the shock of big-city life convulsed not only newly urbanized societies but their literature. Landmark frescoes of metropolitan hubbub and social fragmentation emerged from cities old and new, from the Dublin of Joyce&#39;s “Ulysses” to Alfred Döblin&#39;s “Berlin Alexanderplatz” and the New York of John Dos Passos&#39;s “Manhattan Transfer.” (Cela and Dos Passos shared an inspiration in the Basque novelist Pío Baroja.) Once a proud imperial hub, the Madrid of Cela&#39;s seething panorama has slipped into anxious, threadbare insecurity after Spain&#39;s ruinous and fratricidal civil war. On its hectic streets his throng of strivers, grafters, grifters and chancers sweat to get ahead, or just get by, while “something like sorrow floats in the air and strikes into people&#39;s hearts.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5" target="_blank" class="icon none">16 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/16-books-we-read-this-week-e234b3a5"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824518?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> William F. Buckley&#39;s travels, the era of grand national plans, new fiction from Ann Patchett and more.</p></div></div><p> Born in Galicia, with English, Italian and local ancestry, Cela (1916-2002) had scandalized the Spanish literary scene with the bleak determinism of his 1942 debut, “The Family of Pascual Duarte,” a murderer&#39;s confession often bracketed with Camus&#39;s “The Stranger.” Yet the future Nobel laureate in literature (in 1989) was never a straightforward radical. He fought for the nationalists in the Civil War and served as a censor for Franco&#39;s victorious regime. Ironically, the Spanish authorities banned “The Hive” all the same for its sexual frankness; it first appeared in Buenos Aires. By 1953, the scholar JM Cohen had translated it into English with the help of the exiled Spanish author Arturo Barea.</p><p> In one of the seven prefaces to various editions that front James Womack&#39;s savory new translation, Cela reckons that his novel has 160 characters. Other critics have counted over 200, in a mere 262 pages. Over three winter days, as Hitler&#39;s forces falter on distant battlefields, Cela jump-cuts from scene to scene with cinematic brevity. Terse, urgent, agile, the narrative skips from life to life, mind to mind, with all the breakneck hurry of the urban crowd. One glance may seem to fix a character—Doña Matilde is “fat, dirty and pretentious”—yet when we meet the same personality again, other facets come to light. A group of core figures recur, from the hapless, idealistic poet Martín Marco and the ambitious Moisés family, with their three eligible daughters, to barman Celestino, print-shop worker Victorita, streetwalker Purita and café owner Doña Rosa, the last a bullying neighborhood bigwig who acts “like she&#39;s a regional governor.”</p><p> Mr. Womack catches the bitter comic zest of Cela&#39;s style. Dread and hardship mostly breed not kindness and solidarity but cunning, cynicism and passivity. “Madrid&#39;s a village,” we learn, one in which toxic gossip spreads fast. In “this world where everything has fallen to pieces,” bankruptcy and disgrace lurk around the corner for even the swankiest business-owners. For young women, prostitution—either overt or politely disguised—can look like the only exit. The selfless Victorita, with her consumptive boyfriend, frets that she cannot turn down an indecent proposal; Nati won&#39;t explain why she now dresses like a “princess.”</p><p> Meanwhile, postwar trauma hangs over “The Hive” like low December clouds: It&#39;s “just one of those things” for Purita to have seen her father shot and mother die, “malnourished and tubercular.” A respected physician buys 13-year-old Merche, an “unplucked fruit,” after war smashes her family: “Some of them died; others emigrated.” Cela had a reputation for misanthropic mischief, but his novel tempers its asperity with aching tenderness. There are moments in the print shop when Victorita feels the cold and “wants to cry, wants so very much to cry.” But life, and the city, must go on.</p><p> Busy but becalmed, Cela&#39;s Madrid thrums with ceaseless activity without any real movement. The hive becomes a giant jail with no remission or escape in view. Except, perhaps, for the child from a Gypsy family who sings in scene after scene. To him—like a true artist—“everything that happens is a miracle.” In the little flamenco singer&#39;s clan, people may still live “with absolute freedom and autonomy.” Elsewhere, power seems invisible and implacable. For Martín, his worries feel like fate: “It&#39;s uncontrollable, it&#39;s like the tides.”</p><p> Mr. Womack&#39;s translation boasts a lively pace and a rich demotic tang. Occasionally, his English idioms seem to swing back and forth between midcentury London and New York. So gay Señor Suárez, “alias the Snapperette,” gets called both a pansy (mostly American) and a poofter (distinctly British)—even a “muppet,” surely unheard-of on either side of the Atlantic in 1943. Whatever the epithets thrown at him, the Snapperette dares to rebel. Much more common is the obedience of the “good conformist” cop Morrazo, a Galician who “never got above himself” in a city—and a nation—now ruled in the name of piety and order.</p><p> For all its sadness, Cela&#39;s laconic, swift-moving prose pushes forward with exhilarating energy. As café-table intrigue gives way to furtive erotic rendezvous or street-corner backchat, urban bustle and banter can spark its own fleeting happiness. When night falls, Martín relishes the “deep and implacable emptiness” of his meditative walks. He finds in park benches, with their random occupiers, “an anthology of everything unpleasant and almost everything joyous.” “The Hive” hosts just such a teeming congregation of wayward needs, fears and drives. As for those “vast human enigmas,” the city can&#39;t stop to hear an answer.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Tonkin is the author of “The 100 Best Novels in Translation.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hive-review-fiction-madrid-faces-in-the-crowd-399854da</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hive-review-fiction-madrid-faces-in-the-crowd-399854da<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>